                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d327">
                <head>No. 327.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Sir <persName type="from">L. S. Sackville West</persName> to
                        Mr. <persName type="to">Bayard</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1886-12-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">December</hi> 24, 1886</date>. (Received December
                        27.)</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to your note<note n="*"
                        xml:id="d327fn1">Printed, <ref target="frus1886#pg_425">p. 425 Foreign
                            Relations, 1886</ref>.</note> of the 11th ultimo, I have the honor to
                    inform you that I am requested by the Earl of Iddesleigh to acquaint you that
                    Her Majesty’s Government have desired the Canadian Government to furnish them
                    with a report on the circumstances attending the alleged inhospitable treatment
                    of United States fishing schooners <hi rend="italic">Laura Say ward</hi> and <hi
                        rend="italic">Jennie Seavers</hi> by the Canadian authorities.</p>
                <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">L. S. Sackville West.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
